    body: "More than one in four American adults between the ages of 45 and 64 is caring for an aging parent while still raising or supporting an adult child. The Pew Research Center calls this the sandwich generation, and the demands on these caregivers are unlike anything previous generations faced. Your mother may need rides to dialysis three days a week. Your father is starting to repeat questions. Your twenty-six-year-old moved back home after a layoff. Your daughter and her two kids need a place to land while she finishes nursing school. You still have a job, a marriage, a body that is no longer twenty-five, and maybe, somewhere on the bottom of the list, your own hopes for retirement.\n\nThe instinct in this situation is to keep pushing through. Many sandwich caregivers add hours to their day, drop their own doctor visits, cancel friendships, and survive on coffee and worry. After two or three years of that pattern, the body sends a bill: high blood pressure, weight gain, depression, or a real medical event that forces a pause. The hard truth is that you cannot care for two generations at once if you do not also care for yourself. This is not a feel-good slogan. It is a practical statement, the way a pilot cannot guide a plane safely without oxygen.\n\nThe goal of this guide is not to make the work disappear, because the work is real and important. The goal is to give you a structure: a way to see the whole picture, to share the load, to set fair limits with everyone you love, and to protect the energy you need to keep going for years, not weeks. You will not get it perfect, and that is fine. The families who do best are not the families with the smartest plan. They are the families that talk openly, accept help, and adjust as life changes.\n\nThis guide walks through seven practical moves: taking honest stock of what each generation actually needs, holding a family meeting that produces real commitments, sharing the work with siblings and adult children, using community resources you may have overlooked, protecting your marriage and friendships, planning for the financial squeeze, and watching for the warning signs of burnout. Read it once through, then come back to the steps that match where you are stuck. Print the worksheet at the end and use it with your family. Some of these conversations will be hard. They are still better than the conversation you will have in the emergency room if you ignore the warning signs for too long.",
