    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "Nearly half of American parents with adult children have given them money in the past year, according to a 2024 survey from Bankrate. The average amount is over $1,400, and many parents give far more, sometimes thousands per month, sometimes for years. The reasons are real: a layoff, a divorce, student loans, a medical bill, a chance to buy a first home. Most parents want to help when help is needed. The problem is that many parents do not have a clear plan for when to say yes, when to say no, and when to offer a different kind of support instead. Without a plan, the requests can stretch the parent's own budget thin and create a pattern where the adult child stays dependent longer than is good for either side.\n\nSetting boundaries with adult children about money is not about being cold or punishing. It is about being honest. You have your own bills, your own retirement, and a finite amount of time to save for the years when you can no longer work. An adult child who relies on a steady flow of parent money will not learn the financial skills they need for a long, independent life. The hardest part of this conversation is that love and money mix in ways that can feel raw. The best parents are the ones who can separate the two: I love you completely, and the answer to this specific request is not yes.\n\nFinancial planners and family therapists who work with this issue every day agree on a few core ideas. First, decide in advance how much you can afford to give in a year, in total, before any request comes in. Second, treat every gift as a gift, not a loan, unless you put the loan in writing with clear repayment terms. Third, never sacrifice your own retirement savings to bail out an adult child, because retirement money cannot be borrowed back. Fourth, offer help in forms beyond cash whenever possible: a paid-for class, a budgeting session together, or a job lead. Fifth, talk to your spouse so the two of you are aligned before either of you answers a request.\n\nThis guide walks through how to have these conversations with kindness and clarity. The goal is not to make your child feel ashamed for asking, and not to make you feel guilty for saying no when no is the right answer. The goal is to build a healthy financial relationship that can last for the rest of your life together.",
